@node Starting transcription from Emacs
@section Starting transcription from Emacs

Two commands launch transcription:

@itemize
@item
@samp{M-x eve-transcribe} prompts for a directory, scans for media files, and
starts @samp{eve transcribe} asynchronously.  While it runs, Eve shows a visible
@samp{Eve: transcribing…} mode-line status.  On success the manifest opens
automatically in eve-mode.

@item
@samp{M-x eve-dired-transcribe} runs from Dired using the marked files (or the
file at point when nothing is marked).
@end itemize

On failure, the @samp{*eve transcribe*} buffer appears so you can inspect the error
output.

@node Backends
@section Backends

@samp{eve transcribe} supports three backends:

@multitable {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Backend
@tab Flag
@tab Notes
@item @samp{faster-whisper}
@tab @samp{--backend faster-whisper}
@tab Default.  Fast, local, good accuracy.
@item @samp{transformers}
@tab @samp{--backend transformers}
@tab HuggingFace models.  Needs optional deps.
@item @samp{nemo}
@tab @samp{--backend nemo}
@tab NVIDIA NeMo.  Needs optional deps.
@end multitable

The @samp{--verbatim} flag (on by default in Emacs) biases @samp{faster-whisper} toward
preserving disfluencies and filler words.  For @samp{transformers} and @samp{nemo},
choose a verbatim-friendly model instead.

Good starting points:
@itemize
@item
@samp{transformers}: @samp{nyrahealth/CrisperWhisper}
@item
@samp{nemo}: @samp{nvidia/parakeet-ctc-1.1b}
@end itemize

