@node Navigation
@section Navigation

@multitable {aaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Key
@tab Command
@tab Description
@item @samp{j} / @samp{n}
@tab @samp{eve-next-segment}
@tab Move to next segment.
@item @samp{k} / @samp{p}
@tab @samp{eve-previous-segment}
@tab Move to previous segment.
@end multitable

@node Deletion and restoration
@section Deletion and restoration

@itemize
@item
@samp{d} (@samp{eve-delete-word}) — marks the word at point as deleted.  Deleted
words are hidden in the buffer (@samp{eve-hide-deleted-mode}) and excluded from
compilation.  The operation is non-destructive: the word remains in the JSON
and can be restored.

@item
@samp{D} (@samp{eve-delete-segment}) — marks the entire current segment as deleted.
@end itemize

Deleted content is shown or hidden with @samp{C-c C-h} (@samp{eve-hide-deleted-mode}).

@node Splitting and merging
@section Splitting and merging

@itemize
@item
@samp{s} or @samp{|} (@samp{eve-split-segment}) — splits the current segment at point,
creating two segments with the text and timing divided at the cut.

@item
@samp{m} or @samp{)} (@samp{eve-merge-with-next}) — merges the current segment with the
one below, combining text and adjusting the end time.
@end itemize

@node Reordering
@section Reordering

@itemize
@item
@samp{J} (@samp{eve-move-segment-down}) — move the current segment one position down.
@item
@samp{K} (@samp{eve-move-segment-up}) — move the current segment one position up.
@end itemize

@node Markers and sections
@section Markers and sections

Press @samp{o} (@samp{eve-insert-marker}) to insert a marker above the current segment.
Markers act as named section headings.  They appear in the buffer as bold
titles.

When you compile with @samp{C-c C-c} while point is on a marker, only the segments
in that section are compiled.  This is useful for working on one chapter of a
longer video.

@node Inline editing
@section Inline editing

Press @samp{e} (@samp{eve-dwim-edit}) to edit the text or metadata of the segment at
point.  The command adapts to context: on a word it edits the spoken text; on
a marker it edits the title.

@node Metadata
@section Metadata

@multitable {aaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Key
@tab Command
@tab Description
@item @samp{t}
@tab @samp{eve-toggle-tag}
@tab Toggle a tag on the segment at point.
@item @samp{i}
@tab @samp{eve-edit-speaker}
@tab Set the speaker label for the segment.
@item @samp{r}
@tab @samp{eve-edit-start-end}
@tab Edit the segment's start/end timecodes.
@item @samp{C-c C-n}
@tab @samp{eve-edit-notes}
@tab Edit free-form notes for the segment.
@end multitable

@node Undo and redo
@section Undo and redo

@itemize
@item
@samp{u} (@samp{eve-undo}) — undo the last edit.
@item
@samp{C-r} (@samp{eve-redo}) — redo a previously undone edit.
@end itemize

Eve maintains its own undo stack separate from Emacs's built-in undo.

@node Validation
@section Validation

Eve validates the manifest automatically on every save (controlled by
@samp{eve-validation-on-save}).  Manual validation runs with @samp{C-c C-v}
(@samp{eve-validate}).  Timing inconsistencies are reported in the echo area.

@node Filler Words
@chapter Filler Words

@menu
* Concept::
* Configuration: Configuration (1). 
* Commands::
* Auto-tagging on file open::
@end menu

@node Concept
@section Concept

Filler words ("um", "uh", "you know") clutter transcripts.  Eve's filler
workflow is non-destructive: words are @emph{tagged} as fillers first, then
@emph{optionally deleted}.  Tagged fillers are highlighted in the buffer with a
distinct face and excluded from compilation.  You can untag them at any time.

@node Configuration (1)
@section Configuration

@lisp
;; Plain strings — single words or multi-word phrases
(setq eve-filler-phrases '("um" "uh" "you know" "to be honest with you"))
@end lisp

@samp{eve-filler-phrases} stores phrases as plain strings.  Matching is
case-insensitive and ignores punctuation.  The list is persisted when you use
the interactive add commands.

The legacy @samp{eve-filler-regex} variable is still honoured for backwards
compatibility but @samp{eve-filler-phrases} is preferred.

@node Commands
@section Commands

@multitable {aaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Key
@tab Command
@tab Description
@item @samp{f}
@tab @samp{eve-dwim-filler}
@tab Add the word at point to phrases and retag; or delete region as filler.
@item @samp{F}
@tab @samp{eve-delete-fillers}
@tab Mark all tagged fillers as deleted.
@item @samp{C-c C-d}
@tab @samp{eve-delete-fillers}
@tab Same as @samp{F} from the @samp{C-c} prefix map.
@item —
@tab @samp{M-x eve-tag-fillers}
@tab Tag all matching words in the buffer.
@item —
@tab @samp{M-x eve-add-filler-at-point}
@tab Add the word at point to @samp{eve-filler-phrases} and retag.
@item —
@tab @samp{M-x eve-add-filler-region}
@tab Add the selected phrase to @samp{eve-filler-phrases} and retag.
@end multitable

@node Auto-tagging on file open
@section Auto-tagging on file open

Fillers are tagged automatically every time a TJM manifest is opened.  If you
add a new phrase to @samp{eve-filler-phrases}, reopen the file or run
@samp{M-x eve-tag-fillers} to apply the updated list.

@node B-Roll
@chapter B-Roll

@menu
* Concept: Concept (1). 
