@node Concept (1)
@section Concept

B-roll is supplementary footage that plays over (or instead of) the main
recording.  Eve supports three compositing modes:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Replace} (default) — the b-roll clip completely replaces the source video
for the duration of the segment.  The source audio is kept unless you change
the audio policy.

@item
@strong{Pip} (picture-in-picture) — the b-roll is scaled down and composited on
top of the source video.  You control position and size.

@item
@strong{Overlay} — alias for replace.  Treated identically by the renderer.
@end itemize

@node Editing b-roll metadata
@section Editing b-roll metadata

Press @samp{b} (@samp{eve-edit-broll}) on a segment to set or modify its b-roll.  The
command prompts for each field in turn:

@multitable {aaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Field
@tab Prompt
@tab Description
@item @samp{file}
@tab "B-roll file"
@tab Path to a video, image, or @samp{.json} template.  Blank clears the b-roll.
@item @samp{mode}
@tab "Mode (overlay/replace/pip)"
@tab Compositing mode (see above).
@item @samp{audio}
@tab "Audio (source/mute/broll)"
@tab Which audio track the rendered segment uses.
@item @samp{start_offset}
@tab "Start offset (MM:SS or seconds)"
@tab Where to begin playback in the b-roll clip.
@item @samp{duration}
@tab "Duration (MM:SS or seconds)"
@tab How long the b-roll plays; blank uses the segment duration.
@item @samp{still}
@tab "Treat as still image?"
@tab Auto-detected for @samp{.png}, @samp{.jpg}, etc.  Loops the image for the segment.
@item @samp{continue}
@tab "Continue from previous?"
@tab Part of a continuation chain (see below).
@end multitable

Additional keys:

@multitable {aaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Key
@tab Command
@tab Description
@item @samp{B}
@tab @samp{eve-toggle-broll-continue}
@tab Copy b-roll from the previous segment and mark as continuation.
@item @samp{C-c C-b}
@tab @samp{eve-edit-broll-placeholders}
@tab Edit placeholder values for the current segment.
@end multitable

B-roll metadata is stored in the segment's @samp{edit.broll} field in the JSON
manifest.

@node Compositing modes in detail
@section Compositing modes in detail

@menu
* Replace mode::
* Pip mode::
@end menu

@node Replace mode
@subsection Replace mode

The b-roll video replaces the source video entirely.  The renderer trims the
b-roll to the segment's duration, starting at @samp{start_offset}.  If the b-roll
is shorter than the segment, it is extended to fit.

When @samp{still} is true, the image is looped for the full segment duration using
@samp{ffmpeg -loop 1}.

@node Pip mode
@subsection Pip mode

The b-roll is scaled and positioned as an inset window over the source.
Position and size are controlled by a @samp{position} object in the JSON:

@example
@{
  "file": "demo-recording.mp4",
  "mode": "pip",
  "position": @{
    "x": 0.05,
    "y": 0.05,
    "width": 0.3
  @}
@}
@end example

@multitable {aaaaaaa} {aaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Field
@tab Default
@tab Description
@item @samp{x}
@tab @samp{0.05}
@tab Horizontal offset as a fraction of the main video width (0.0--1.0).
@item @samp{y}
@tab @samp{0.05}
@tab Vertical offset as a fraction of the main video height (0.0--1.0).
@item @samp{width}
@tab @samp{0.3}
@tab Width of the pip window as a fraction of the main video width.
@end multitable

The height is calculated automatically to preserve the b-roll's aspect ratio.

@node Audio policy
@section Audio policy

Each b-roll entry has an @samp{audio} field that controls which audio track
appears in the rendered segment:

@itemize
@item
@samp{source} (default) — keep the original recording's audio.
@item
@samp{broll} — use the audio track from the b-roll clip.  Not available for
still images.
@item
@samp{mute} — no audio for this segment.
@end itemize

@node JSON templates
@section JSON templates

When the @samp{file} field points to a @samp{.json} file instead of a media file, eve
treats it as a @strong{template}.  The template JSON has this structure:

@example
@{
  "template": "lower-third.png",
  "overlays": [
    @{
      "placeholder": "SPEAKER_NAME",
      "fontsize": 36,
      "color": "white",
      "x": 80,
      "y": 620,
      "boxColor": "black@@0.6"
    @},
    @{
      "placeholder": "SPEAKER_TITLE",
      "fontsize": 24,
      "color": "#cccccc",
      "x": 80,
      "y": 665
    @}
  ],
  "placeholders": @{
    "SPEAKER_NAME": "Full Name",
    "SPEAKER_TITLE": "Job Title"
  @}
@}
@end example

@itemize
@item
@samp{template} — path to the actual media file (image or video).
@item
@samp{overlays} — a list of text overlays rendered with ffmpeg @samp{drawtext}.
Each overlay references a @samp{placeholder} key by name.
@item
@samp{placeholders} — default values for each placeholder.  Segment-level
overrides (set via @samp{C-c C-b}) take precedence.
@end itemize

@menu
