@node Overlay fields
@subsection Overlay fields

Each overlay in the @samp{overlays} array supports:

@multitable {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Field
@tab Description
@item @samp{placeholder}
@tab Name of the placeholder key this overlay renders.
@item @samp{fontsize} (or @samp{size})
@tab Font size in pixels.
@item @samp{color} (or @samp{fontColor})
@tab Font colour (ffmpeg colour syntax: name, @samp{#rrggbb}, @samp{white@@0.8}).
@item @samp{x} (or @samp{position_x})
@tab Horizontal position (pixels or ffmpeg expression like @samp{(w-text_w)/2}).
@item @samp{y} (or @samp{position_y})
@tab Vertical position (pixels or ffmpeg expression).
@item @samp{align}
@tab Set to @samp{"center"} to auto-centre horizontally and vertically.
@item @samp{font} (or @samp{fontfile})
@tab Path to a @samp{.ttf} or @samp{.otf} font file.
@item @samp{boxColor} (or @samp{box_color})
@tab Background box colour (e.g. @samp{black@@0.6} for 60% opacity).
@item @samp{shadowColor} / @samp{shadow_x} / @samp{shadow_y}
@tab Drop shadow parameters.
@item @samp{start} / @samp{end} / @samp{duration}
@tab Time window (seconds) during which the overlay is visible.
@end multitable

@node Concrete example lower-third title card
@subsection Concrete example: lower-third title card

Suppose you have a background image @samp{lower-third.png} and you want to show
the speaker's name and title during a segment.

@enumerate
@item
Create the template file @samp{assets/lower-third.json}:

@example
@{
  "template": "assets/lower-third.png",
  "overlays": [
    @{
      "placeholder": "NAME",
      "fontsize": 42,
      "color": "white",
      "x": 80,
      "y": 620,
      "font": "assets/Inter-Bold.ttf",
      "boxColor": "black@@0.5"
    @},
    @{
      "placeholder": "ROLE",
      "fontsize": 28,
      "color": "#cccccc",
      "x": 80,
      "y": 672,
      "font": "assets/Inter-Regular.ttf"
    @}
  ],
  "placeholders": @{
    "NAME": "Speaker Name",
    "ROLE": "Speaker Role"
  @}
@}
@end example

@item
In eve-mode, press @samp{b} on the segment where you want the title card.
Set @samp{file} to @samp{assets/lower-third.json}.  Set @samp{mode} to @samp{replace}.

@item
Press @samp{C-c C-b} to edit placeholders for this segment:

@example
Placeholder NAME (default Speaker Name): Jane Doe
Placeholder ROLE (default Speaker Role): Product Lead
New placeholder key (blank to finish):
@end example

@item
Compile with @samp{C-c C-c}.  The rendered segment shows @samp{lower-third.png}
with "Jane Doe" and "Product Lead" burned in as text overlays at the
specified positions and sizes.
@end enumerate

Each segment can override different placeholder values from the same
template.  The template is reused; only the text changes.

@node Placeholders without templates
@section Placeholders without templates

You can also set placeholder key-value pairs directly on a segment without
a JSON template, using @samp{C-c C-b}.  These are stored in the manifest under
@samp{edit.broll.placeholders} and are available for any overlay definitions.

@node Continuation chains
@section Continuation chains

When a single b-roll clip should span multiple consecutive segments, use
continuation chains:

@enumerate
@item
Press @samp{b} on the first segment and configure the b-roll normally.
@item
Move to the next segment and press @samp{B} (@samp{eve-toggle-broll-continue}).
@end enumerate

@samp{B} copies the b-roll metadata from the nearest preceding segment that has
b-roll, then auto-calculates:

@itemize
@item
@samp{continue}: set to @samp{true}.
@item
@samp{start_offset}: previous offset + previous segment duration, so playback
continues seamlessly from where the last segment left off.
@item
@samp{duration}: remaining duration of the b-roll clip (if the original had a
duration set).
@end itemize

Repeat @samp{B} on each subsequent segment in the chain.  The renderer treats the
entire chain as one continuous b-roll playback — the clip advances smoothly
across segment boundaries without restarting.

